'\" t
.TH "UvTTY" "7" "" "uvtty"
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.SH "NAME"
UvTTY - User session terminal session
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.B uvtty
is very similar to
.BR vtty (7)
only a UvTTY runs as the user, instead of from system services.
Namely a
.BR socat (1)
server, of which instead of starting a getty as root,
.B uvtty-session
starts the user's desired shell on the pty socat creates. And 
then starts a
.BR socat (1)
client that runs under the
.BR foot (1)
terminal emulator, of which runs under wlroots-based
.BR cage (1)
Wayland server, that also runs as the user.
.SH "STARTING"
To start a UvTTY, typically from your display manager, select the
.B Fullscreen Terminal
wayland session option, and then log in.
.SH "STARTING OTHER DISPLAY SERVERS"
It is possible to start display servers, (or anything that uses
/dev/dri/cardX or /dev/fbX) from a UvTTY using the
.BR uvtty-launch (1)
command. The frontend is temporarily suspended by
.B uvtty-launch
to allow the desired program to take control, such as
.B startx
or
.B weston
and the like.
.SH "ACCESSIBILITY"
.B uvtty
supports an optional accessible mode, where all the text is
read by the fenrir screen reader.
.SH "CONFIGURATION"
.PP
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/kanshiconfig.conf
is the configuration file for a small daemon that ensures that
.BR cage (1)
uses clone mode. This can be overridden by
.B ~/.config/uvtty/kanshiconfig.conf
for per-user settings.
.PP
By creating a
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/accessiblemode
file. (it can be empty), enables the accessible mode for all users.
Creating a
.B ~/.config/uvtty/accessiblemode
file enables accessible mode for one user.
.PP
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/footkiosk.conf
is the configuration for the
.BR foot (1)
terminal emulator.  This can be overridden by
.B ~/.config/uvtty/footkiosk.conf
for per-user settings.
.PP
The directory
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/
is set as
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME
so that any other library configuration files, like
.B ~/.config/xkb
can be set by an administrator. This is applicable to the frontend
only, not the user processes running on the backend.
.SH "BOOT OPTIONS"
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkblayout=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBLAYOUT
for the UvTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkbmodel=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBMODEL
for the UvTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkbvariant=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBVARIANT
for the UvTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkboptions=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBOPTIONS
for the UvTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vttyaccessible
.RS 12
Enables accessibility mode for the UvTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B novttyaccessible
.RS 12
Disables accessibility mode for for the UvTTYs. This always takes
precedence so that in case there is a problem with
.BR fenrir (1)
the system is not unusable.
.RE

.SH NOTES
Only the first GPU in the seat is used. The UvTTYs will not span to screens on the second card.
.SH See Also:
.BR uvtty-launch (1)
